< text>
Fitdog is my go to place for boarding, day care and grooming. The staff is always beyond courteous and helpful. My dog has been a fitdog member for about 7 years. Daily report cards and photos keep me informed during her stay. The guests are kept in their separate  dens during their stay and they have a solid emergency plan in case they need to exit the dogs. I did not find this at other facilities, some of which let the dogs sleep together in open spaces. Besides my rave reviews, after all these years my dog is always excited to arrive and walks straight to the door that seperates the play area from the front desk. Would give 10 stars if I could!< /text>

<rate>1</rate><Review>They literally almost killed my cat.

TL;DR: didn't give a dehydrate cat water, left her freezing overnight, tried to physically hand her back with a catheter and IV needle still in her, told me I "didn't know anything", repeatedly pushed for expensive needless extras, they made a value judgement about a bank issue, disturbing lack of empathy

My two year old cat had a case of worms, and she stopped eating and drinking for several days meaning not only was she clearly dehydrated, but she wouldn't take the worm meds. We took her to Blue Cross, told them EXACTLY what was going on. Specifically the lack of food and water. We drop her off, and get a call about an hour later saying they're recommending bloodwork, an xray and some other stuff, estimated $600 we say ok. We go to get her right before they close, SURPRISE! it's going to be almost $900. Well, there's a bank issue with that much funds. Being very clear, a bank issue, not a lack of funds issue (not that that would make it any more ok). Because this is right before closing, they tell us they're off at 5, and therefore they can't give us our cat back before we pay tomorrow. After, that is, demanding "why can't you just borrow that from somebody".
Next day, we get a call at 9:30 am saying our cat is doing so much worse, she's probably going to die, and also SURPRISE NUMBER 2 they forgot an extra charge of $150 they didn't add to yesterday's bill! Yay! At this point we told them to do ONLY what was required to rehydrate her, and we paid the bill.
We get there to pick her up (fully paid at this point) and a vet tech brings her out, hands us a random bag of stuff and says "you have to hurry because she has the Iv needle in her". Absolutely gobsmacked, we asked more questions, finding out that not only did she still have the IV and catheter still in her, but they hadn't bothered to administer the meds, and the "special equipment" we'd been charged for was a target heating pad, because nobody had given her food or water overnight.
After being horrified and demanding they take it out, we get ANOTHER call, saying the doctor wants to do more x-rays and tests because "we still don't know and she's going to die otherwise". We said no.  The admin manager I spoke to, when asked why she hadn't been given IV fluids, responds that " well she didn't seem dehydrated" despite us telling them she' hadn't eaten or drank in 4 days. We also get emailed a bill for the IV fluids separately, with 5 different items listed on it including several antibiotics. When I challenge that, having only authorized the IV fluids I get told "ok, you don't know anything" in probably the most condescending way possible.
Probably the icing on the cake was looking through the record sheets, and seeing "lack of funds" literally scrawled across the page.

To sum up: my cat is fine now. She starting eating three days after this ordeal, a day after we starting gently syringe feeding her water which we should evidently have done and saved ourselves over $1000.< /Review>< Pics>

<username>Lauren Takacs<//username><resp>None<//resp><review>I have taken all of my animals here and they've always taken great care and caution to them. The staff is very friendly. My German Shepherd is fairly of age and they are very considerate and they try to bring her to the closest room so she doesn't have to walk far, or they will bring some of their equipment to her. One of the veterinarians also showed me how to do some physical therapy techniques on both my dogs to make their arthritis more bearable, less painful.

My German Shepherd had to get surgery recently to remove a fairly large tumor on her elbow. They kept her overnight to monitor her, make sure she ate, and gave her a nice bandage/cast on her arm. Unfortunately the bandage ended up falling off the day I took her home. I had hoped they wouldn't have charged me for a new bandage because the first one shouldn't have fallen off, but they charged me $44 for a new bandage. Friendly neighborhood full service veterinary clinic for your pets.  They have several ling-term vets that practice here. Besides the expected services,  they also offer anesthesia-free cleanings once a month.  Reservations are highly recommended specially on weekends.

Like most vets these days, you should review the services that will be done and tell them to skip unnecessary ones.  Otherwise your bill will clim quickly. Their prescriptions are usually 15-20% higher than online but they do have most of them in stock.</text>

<text>I don't do these often, but this place needs to be recognized.

If you've ever been to a bad vet, then you know that feeling of a standoffish or cold approach you can get from some. The folks at Blue Cross Pet Hospital are the exact opposite. Across the board the staff is there to help you with your pet. They are warm and engaging from the first phone call onward.

After over a year of visting another nearby vet, this was a welcome respite from the issues my little buddy had been going through.

I've read other reviews complaining about the price or other issues, and I'm completly confident in saying those reviews are misleading. The pricing is VERY reasonable and the care they provide is outstanding.

The vet that examined my cat, Dr. Gros, was very thorough, explained everything to me in detail and made sure that any questions I had were answered. She also invited me to get back in touch if there was something I'd forgotten in the moments of the visit.

These folks CARE about our furry friends. They know what they are doing and they understand the stress we are under when our buddies are not well.

If I could give more than five stars, I would.

You will be hard pressed to find better care for your furball or, as importantly, for yourself.< /text><gmapID>0x80c295ef10a3ee59:0x4067531a98670c4f< /gmapID></record>

<user>116794028849856097429< /user>< Name>
Brian Orosco< /Name>
< date>
1403187634887< /date>
<rating>3<//rating><Review>I have mixed feelings about this place. There are some big pluses and big minuses, which is why I'm at 3 stars, right in the middle.

Pluses:
They do provide very good care and are well staffed with nice people. I have a mini dachshund who I've been bringing here for about a year and a half. He's super low maintenance, but has had a few moments when he's needed big procedures ("big" meaning costly) or emergency visits and he's always been treated well and had his issues taken care of. A couple of those were false alarms, but I'm not a vet, and couldn't have known unless I took him in. He also had a full teeth cleaning and they did a great job.

Minuses:
EXPENSIVE!! Anyone who tells you this place is reasonably priced is full of it. Not to mention they nickel and dime you on everything and will ALWAYS up-sell you or include extras that sound like requirements. It's unfortunate because they operate like a profitable business, not a hospital. Granted, they are good at what they do, but they certainly don't try to make it easy for you. It's very frustrating to me because it taints every experience. I hate that I have to be skeptical of every little procedure and medication and try to figure out if my dog actually needs it, or if it's extra. Most of the time I begrudgingly agree to whatever and take the hit, but others I sound like the untrusting parent, which makes me feel like a dick when they're the ones forcing me into that position.

Also, because they operate like a business, the vets/staff can often be a little impersonal and I sometimes question their diagnosis/treatment process. It doesn't really feel like they are trying... certainly not negligent, just kinda like they have a general list for certain symptoms and its easier to just do all of them because then they don't really have to think too hard about it and, hey, more treatment means more money! Don't get me wrong, I'm not against paying for quality care, but there's a better way to do it. I used to go to Presidio Way when I lived in San Francisco. They were expensive too, but their vets were super personable, very caring, and awesome. They always remembered me and gave it to me straight. They would give me options and talk me through everything so I didn't  have to guess, and they didn't nickel and dime me. I felt like a patient, not walking wallet. It instilled confidence and trust, not skepticism.

Conclusion:
It's like owning a BMW without a warranty... the dealership will always charge you an arm and a leg for everything whether you need it or not, but your car will always run great when they're done. I look at as a necessary evil. I care about my dog, so I put up with it, and I'll continue to do so until something better comes along (which I hope is soon!).</Review>< pictures>
None< /pictures>

< Review>
Back in January our 13 year old husky/shepard rescue had a seizure...I thought she'd had a stroke and was ready to let her go.  The vet we'd used for years isn't open Saturdays but I knew my daughter was using someone she really liked, so I called her.  We were the first to be seen, Dr. Howe asked many questions about the seizure while doing a table exam on poor Ramona, who could not stand.  The initial diagnosis was probably vertigo related.  We left Ray for a more thorough exam and tests (while we went for a walk), came back 90 minutes later to a walking-ish, tail-wagging animal, medications, diagnosis and acceptable bill.  I was thrilled with the knowledge, care and attention my Ramona got.  But it get's better.

After recommended dental work, including extractions, Ramona came home in March cleaner, sleeker and less shedding than I've seen in the years since mobile groomers refused bathe her at home (big, jumpy, angry...knew how to get a muzzle off).  Again, healthy mouth, gums and easy recovery from extractions at reasonable cost we understood up front.  So, when I had the big family holiday dinner recently, Ramona spent the morning with Blue Cross for grooming.  While there I asked about some of the vertigo meds, which they price-matched with on-line purveyors, Julie apprised me of needed vacinations (after SHE contacted the previous vet), and my doggie was a happy, clean, cuddleable camper for the guests.

I am a dedicated Blue Cross Pet Hospital fan, for all they do, who they are and the care my current and future pets get.  Unfortunately, my daughter's two kitties moved to Denver!</Review>

We signed our 13 year old son up for a lesson with Chris at Malibu Surf Coach and it was a great experience. Our son had several surfing lessons on a vacation some time ago and so was not a complete beginning, but is certainly very inexperienced. < username>
Kevin Waters</username>
< Text>
When I was a kid this park was my favorite place to be in 1975-1978. I remember the summer club for kids was Get High On Life. We get free lunch and go to Gladstone High pool after. I also remember the trip to San Diego.  We camped at  Boy Scout Camping area near the Zoo. We took the Amtrak down there and back.

There is a tree still there that I climbed on and carved my x-girlfriend and my initials in. I was there in 2005 and they are still there. Never married her...  :(
I remember one year they had a toys for tots event there,  I do not remember who was famous at the time the showed up but I do remember that event.

The Park has a deal you could check something out but you have to leave something important so the park could be sure you came back.  They had a huge ball that was about 7 feet round.  kids would run and slam themselves against it.  There was a little boy that ran towards the ball and  a much older and big kid slam himself against it and the little kid went flying and landed on the side walk.  The mother freaked out and the park took the ball and flattened it and would not let anyone use it again.

What memories...</Text>

< user_name>
Carm BW<//user_name>
< Text>
The statement that this is one of the best Salvadorian restaurants in LA is overrated. I thought the pupusas' were delicious especially the shrimp and pork, cheese & jalapeno one. The pupusas are made right when you order so  they come up smoking hot but be prepared to wait. Tonight was the first time I tried horchata made with morro seeds instead of rice, the Salvadorian way. The color and taste is very different. It is also not as sweet. The service was slow because only one person was working, the camarones entomatados was okay, the casamiento was very salty and free parking was available in the lot.<//Text>

Meanwhile, 5:00 came and went and, remarkably, the x-ray tech was actually sitting around waiting for the front office to enter me into the system so he could take me back.  The receptionist apologized and said she would get me entered ASAP.  I cannot recall a more dysfunctional operation.  Net net -- I was there ~90 minutes.  Here is my bottom line:  if you can choose a different provider -- DO IT -- it is impossible to be less organized/clueless.  I was referred by Apple Wellness and I will be advising them of my experience and recommendation that they no longer use Valley Radiologists.</review></record>

< review>
The mammographers were very professional and friendly putting you at ease. Unfortunately, my mammo showed an abnormality prompting the  radiologist to come and speak to me.  I asked the radiologists questions so I could understand the pathology and understand her thought process in order to help me make decisions as to how to proceed with my care. And basically asked "so why do you think it is this and not that?" and instead of explaining it to me she thought it was better to respond with a flat "Because I have been doing this for 30 years", which tells the patient absolutely nothing as to what was going on.  I realize this radiologist probably sees at least 10 patients a day, telling them that they may have breast cancer which has probably developed a numbness within her to the fact that she speaking to a patient that is hearing devastating news and is frightened by this result.  I think once a physician no longer has empathy for their patients, it is probably time to retire.  Additionally, I was set up to have a breast biopsy  at one of their other facilities.  On the day of the appointment, I drove 50 miles (in commuter traffic) to find out that their equipment was down and they were unable to perform the biopsy. If the facility was professionally run and common courtesy, one would have thought that they would have contacted the patient and alert them to the fact they were unable to perform the biopsy because their equipment was down and reschedule the appointment to prevent the patient from coming all the way into the office and then be told this.  Worst experience!! And at a time when I is feeling the most vulnerable!  Unprofessionally run, radiologists that seem to really not care about anything, and dysfunctional.</review>
